                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d762">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.20 Defense (M)/135: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-07-25T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 25, 1940—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>149. Department’s 127, July 22, 8 p.m. For your information, the American Consul
                    at Saigon informs the Department<note n="31" xml:id="d762fn31">In telegram of
                        July 24, 3 p.m., not printed.</note> that in his opinion French naval
                    authorities at Saigon will not release the ores discharged from the <hi
                        rend="italic">Selenga</hi> until specific instructions are received from the
                    French Admiralty. He states that the Chinese Consul at Saigon has been informed
                    by the Chungking Government that this question was taken up with the Government
                    in France by the Chinese Embassy and that the French Minister for Foreign
                    Affairs has authorized the release of the wolfram and antimony purchased by this
                    Government.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Welles</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
